following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Conjunctivitis","Scleritis","Episcleritis","Iritis","Optic neuritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E. It may be idiopathic, aggravated by dusty environments, or can occur secondary to underlying autoimmune inflammatory disease, dry eye syndrome or blepharitis. It usually resolves spontaneously and does not affect visual acuity, but lubricating eye drops, and oral anti-inflammatories can be used for comfort.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EScleritis would be much more painful and likely have pain on extra-ocular movements as well photophobia. Conjunctivitis would have more redness and is usually bilateral (as it is infective) and commonly has discharge from the eye. Both iritis and optic neuritis the patient would have more optical complaints such as blurry vision.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Episcleritis does not require any active intervention, apart from lubricating eye drops."],"references":["Jabs DA, Medan A, Dunn JP, Marsh MJ. Episcleritis and scleritis: clinical features and treatment results. American Journal of Ophthalmology. 2000 Oct; 130(4): 469-76."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78158"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1610"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18470"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18470"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b168e64c-03a5-4cbf-bed4-658fde595612.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b168e64c-03a5-4cbf-bed4-658fde595612.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78158"},"attri